observationText: The SK-MEL-90 cell line is a melanoma cell line that expresses a 90 kDa glycoprotein (gp90) on its surface, which was identified as a unique tumor antigen by monoclonal antibodies KF23, KF26 and KF104 derived from immunizing mice with the gp90 antigen.
The gp90 glycoprotein expressed by the SK-MEL-90 cell line was found to bind to concanavalin A, indicating it is a glycosylated protein.
The gp90 glycoprotein from SK-MEL-90 could be immunoprecipitated from cells metabolically labeled with [3H]glucosamine, confirming it is a glycoprotein.
Under non-reducing conditions, the gp90 glycoprotein from SK-MEL-90 had an apparent molecular mass of 85 kDa on SDS-PAGE.
The monoclonal antibody KF23 showed reactivity against the SK-MEL-90 cell line in a titer range of 10^-3 to 10^-6, indicating the gp90 antigen is expressed on the surface of these cells.
